Both ships had reached Japan by February 1898.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/71283113?searchTerm=battleship%20fuji&searchLimits=|title=The Chinese Question|work=Australian Town and Country Journal|pages=31|accessdate=29 July 2012|location=Sydney, Australia}}</ref>
At the start of the Russo-Japanese War in 1904, ''Fuji'' and ''Yashima'' were assigned to the 1st Division of the [[1st Fleet (Imperial Japanese Navy)|1st Fleet]]. They participated in the Battle of Port Arthur on 9 February, when Admiral [[T<U+014D>g<U+014D> Heihachir<U+014D>]] led the 1st Fleet in an attack on the Russian ships of the [[Pacific Fleet (Russia)|Pacific Squadron]] anchored just outside Port Arthur. T<U+014D>g<U+014D> chose to attack the Russian coastal defences with his main armament and engage the Russian ships with his secondary guns. Splitting his fire proved to be a poor decision as his {{convert|8|in|0|adj=on|spell=in}} and six-inch guns inflicted very little damage on the Russian vessels, which concentrated all their fire on the Japanese ships. ''Yashima'' was not struck during the battle, but ''Fuji'' was hit twice, two men being killed and 10 wounded.<ref>Forczyk, pp. 41<U+2013>44</ref>

[[File:Battleship Yashima.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Model of ''Yashima'' with her [[torpedo nets]] deployed, [[National Maritime Museum]], London]]
On 10 March, the two ships blindly bombarded the harbour of Port Arthur from Pigeon Bay, on the southwest side of the [[Liaodong Peninsula]], at a range of {{convert|9.5|km}}, but did little damage.<ref>Brook 1985, p. 269</ref> When they tried again on 22 March, they were attacked by Russian coastal defence guns that had been transferred there, and also from several Russian ships in Port Arthur using observers overlooking Pigeon Bay. The Japanese ships disengaged after ''Fuji'' was hit by a 12-inch shell.<ref name=f4>Forczyk, p. 44</ref>

''Fuji'' and ''Yashima'' participated in the action of 13 April when T<U+014D>g<U+014D> successfully lured out two battleships of the Pacific Squadron. When the Russians spotted the five battleships of the 1st Division, they turned back for Port Arthur and the battleship {{ship|Russian battleship|Petropavlovsk|1897|2}} struck a minefield laid by the Japanese the previous night. The ship sank in less than two minutes after one of her magazines exploded. Emboldened by his success, T<U+014D>g<U+014D> resumed long-range bombardment missions, which prompted the Russians to lay more minefields.<ref>Forczyk, pp. 45<U+2013>46</ref>

On 14 May 1904, the battleships [[Japanese battleship Hatsuse|''Hatsuse'']], {{ship|Japanese battleship|Shikishima||2}}, and ''Yashima'', the [[protected cruiser]] [[Japanese cruiser Kasagi|''Kasagi'']], and the [[dispatch boat]] {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Tatsuta|1894|2}} put to sea to relieve the Japanese blockading force off Port Arthur.<ref>Warner & Warner, p. 279</ref> The following morning, the squadron encountered a Russian minefield. ''Hatsuse'' struck one mine that disabled her steering and ''Yashima'' struck two others when moving to assist ''Hatsuse''.<ref name=l14/> ''Yashima'' was towed away from the minefield, but she was still taking on water at an uncontrollable rate and the crew abandoned ship some five hours later. ''Kasagi'' took ''Yashima'' in tow, but the battleship's [[list (watercraft)|list]] continued to increase and she capsized about three hours later.<ref>Warner & Warner, pp. 279<U+2013>82</ref>

[[File:IJN Fuji 2.jpg|thumb|A postcard of ''Fuji'' in 1905]]
During the Battle of the Yellow Sea in August 1904, ''Fuji'' was not damaged because the Russian ships concentrated their fire on T<U+014D>g<U+014D>'s flagship, the battleship {{ship|Japanese battleship|Mikasa||2}}, which was leading the column.<ref>Forczyk, pp. 52<U+2013>53</ref> In May the following year, during the Battle of Tsushima, ''Fuji'' was hit a dozen times, the most serious of which penetrated the hood of the rear barbette, ignited some exposed propellant charges, killed eight men and wounded nine. After the ammunition fire was put out, the left gun in the barbette resumed firing and apparently delivered the ''[[coup de gr<U+00E2>ce]]'' that sank the battleship {{ship|Russian battleship|Borodino||2}}.<ref>Campbell, p. 263</ref>

On 23 October 1908, ''Fuji'' hosted a dinner for the American Ambassador, [[Thomas J. O'Brien (Michigan politician)|Thomas J. O'Brien]], and the senior officers of the [[Great White Fleet]] during its circumnavigation of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B01E1DC1739E333A25757C2A9669D946997D6CF&scp=8&sq=battleship+and+fuji&st=p|title=Tokio Enthusiasts Nearly Mob Sperry|date=24 October 1908|work=New York Times|accessdate=29 July 2012}}</ref> In 1910, her cylindrical boilers were replaced by Miyabara [[water-tube boiler]]s and her main armament was replaced by Japanese-built guns. ''Fuji'' was reclassified as a first-class [[coast defence ship]] the same year, and undertook training duties in various capacities until disarmed in 1922. Her hulk continued to be used as a floating [[barracks]] and training centre at Yokosuka until 1945.<ref>Jentschura, Jung & Mickel, pp. 16<U+2013>17</ref> ''Fuji'' was damaged by American carrier aircraft during their 18 July 1945 [[attack on Yokosuka]]<ref>Tully</ref> and capsized after the end of the war.<ref>Fukui, p. 54</ref> The ship was scrapped in 1948.<ref name=j7/>

